03963nam a22004935i 9781553393429DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815533934297 a10.1515/97815533934292doi  a(DE-B1597)654849  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLA418.O6bF35 2013 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a379.7131 aFallis, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRethinking Higher Education :bParticipation, Research, and Differentiation /cGeorge Fallis.  a20160314 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQueen's Policy Studies Series ;v18100tFront Matter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tOntario ’s System of Higher Education -- tInstitutional Diferentiation: Mandate and Programs -- tGovernment Policy, Institutional Decision Making, and Isomorphism -- tParticipation: Universal Higher Education Has Been Achieved -- tRethinking Bacalaureate Education -- tGraduate Education and Profesional Education -- tThe New Research Agenda -- tRethinking University Research -- tFurther Diferentiation of the Binary System -- tConclusion: Policy Directions and Implementation -- tHigher Education Policy in a Time of Expenditure Restraint -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author -- tQueen’s Policy Studies Recent Publications0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe basic structure of universities and colleges in Ontario - one focused primarily on expansion and greater access and put in place in the 1960s - is outdated. The system is now large enough, the eligible age group for entering post-secondary studies is shrinking, and participation rates are as high as they are likely to go. In Rethinking Higher Education, George Fallis argues that policy-makers should shift their attention away from growth and towards improving and diversifying the range of programs available and creating new means of program delivery. He calls for increases in honours undergraduate programs and polytechnic education and envisions a group of research-intensive universities responsible for doctoral education. The existing design, Fallis contends, neglects the specific needs of graduate education and research, layering it on top of a system designed for undergraduate education. In addition, there is disconnection between Ontario's Ministry of Training, Colleges, and Universities and the research missions of the universities and colleges themselves. Fallis recommends that Ontario establish a system for documenting and assessing the quality of research published at universities. Thought-provoking and thoroughly argued, Rethinking Higher Education provides a detailed design for higher education in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducation, HigherzOntario. 0aUniversities and collegeszOntario. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978155339342940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781553393429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781553393429/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles